in pencil Alexander, Frank
RADISSON INN
Under Management of Hotel Radisson, Minneapolis
EXCELSIOR, MINN.

June 1st. 1935

Mr. Jack Conroy.
Moberly, Mo.

Dear Mr. Conroy: -
 During the month the American Writers Congress convened - and which I had the honor to attend -

I was dancing in N.Y. at the Hollywood Restaurant, a  mid-town night club. it was my first engagement
there in nearly three years, the last being the Biltmore Hotel.

From April of '34 until January '35 I danced at the Cathay Hotel in Shang-

2
hai, China. Since back various places throughout the U.S. - and at present at a "Gambling Casino":
Raddison Inn, Excelsior, Minn.

My contact with the revolutionary movement has been purely an intellectual one, though my hone in

Detroit - my father is a house painter - was of the working-class.

(This brevity is because I realize you are an intensely busy man.)
My problem is this: - my first novel is being completed. It definitely falls in the proletarian class. Its field

that of child-labor in show-business - subjected, but

3/  I'm sure not injured, to a swiftly-moving, first-person plot, covering an adolescent's life
from 15 to 25. Its title "Decade."

It treats of a peculiar growth that you may or may not know much of. Theatres, night-clubs, etc.

I am convinced of its importance.

Would you write me, tell me what steps I should take? It belongs I fervently hope in the new field

of revolutionary literature.

I expect nothing in a monetary sense - I have my dancing at present. The important thing to me

is to place it in the proper

4) hands. It is my first completed attempt - but surely taps the surface, there is much more.

We close here June 11th - I would appreciate , it possible, an answer by then.
With sincere admiration, I remain respectfull [sic] yours
   Frank Alexander
